<tr>
<td bgcolor="#C3FDB8"><a href="/wiki/Pubmed" title="Pubmed" class="mw-redirect">Pubmed</a> search</td>
<td bgcolor="#EEEEEE" style="border-top:2px solid #dddddd; border-right:2px solid #dddddd"><span class="plainlinks"><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?db=gene&amp;cmd=Link&amp;LinkName=gene_pubmed&amp;from_uid=6469" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?db=gene&amp;cmd=Link&amp;LinkName=gene_pubmed&amp;from_uid=6469" rel="nofollow">[1]</a></span></td>
<td bgcolor="#EEEEEE" style="border-top:2px solid #dddddd; border-right:2px solid #dddddd"><span class="plainlinks"><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?db=gene&amp;cmd=Link&amp;LinkName=gene_pubmed&amp;from_uid=20423" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?db=gene&amp;cmd=Link&amp;LinkName=gene_pubmed&amp;from_uid=20423" rel="nofollow">[2]</a></span></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Sonic hedgehog homolog</b> (SHH) is one of three <a href="/wiki/Protein" title="Protein">proteins</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Mammalian" title="Mammalian" class="mw-redirect">mammalian</a> <a href="/wiki/Hedgehog_(cell_signaling)" title="Hedgehog (cell signaling)" class="mw-redirect">hedgehog</a> family, the others being <a href="/wiki/DHH_(hedgehog)" title="DHH (hedgehog)">desert hedgehog</a> (DHH) and <a href="/wiki/Indian_Hedgehog_(protein)" title="Indian Hedgehog (protein)" class="mw-redirect">Indian hedgehog</a> (IHH). SHH is the best studied <a href="/wiki/Ligand" title="Ligand">ligand</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Hedgehog_(cell_signaling)" title="Hedgehog (cell signaling)" class="mw-redirect">hedgehog signaling pathway</a>. It plays a key role in regulating <a href="/wiki/Vertebrate" title="Vertebrate">vertebrate</a> <a href="/wiki/Organogenesis" title="Organogenesis">organogenesis</a>, such as in the growth of digits on <a href="/wiki/Limb_(anatomy)" title="Limb (anatomy)">limbs</a> and organization of the <a href="/wiki/Brain" title="Brain">brain</a>. Sonic hedgehog is the best established example of a <a href="/wiki/Morphogen" title="Morphogen">morphogen</a> as defined by <a href="/wiki/Lewis_Wolpert" title="Lewis Wolpert">Lewis Wolpert</a>'s <a href="/wiki/French_flag_model" title="French flag model">French flag model</a>—a molecule that <a href="/wiki/Diffusion" title="Diffusion" class="mw-redirect">diffuses</a> to form a concentration gradient and has different effects on the cells of the developing <a href="/wiki/Embryo" title="Embryo">embryo</a> depending on its concentration. SHH remains important in the adult. It controls <a href="/wiki/Cell_division" title="Cell division">cell division</a> of <a href="/wiki/Adult_stem_cell" title="Adult stem cell">adult stem cells</a> and has been implicated in <a href="/wiki/Carcinogenesis" title="Carcinogenesis">development of some cancers</a>.</p>
